In this article, it is mentioned that President Obama spoke with Prime Minister Cameron of the United Kingdom regarding the situation in Libya. They discussed coordinating international efforts to end the violence in Libya and ensure accountability. Both leaders agreed that the main objectives in Libya should be to end brutality and violence, remove Qadhafi from power as quickly as possible, and establish a transition that meets the aspirations of the Libyan people for freedom, dignity, and a representative government. They also agreed to plan for various responses, including surveillance, humanitarian assistance, enforcement of the arms embargo, and a no-fly zone, with the help of NATO. The President expressed appreciation for the UK's partnership at the UN and their provision of humanitarian aid to Libya. They also committed to close coordination on future actions. The article also mentions that the President and the Prime Minister will continue to support Egypt in its efforts towards a successful and peaceful democratic transition. Lastly, they emphasized the importance of international efforts to promote peace and stability in Afghanistan and Pakistan, including their commitment to Afghan-led reconciliation.